04407nam a22005295i 9780300159899DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20092009ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001598997 a10.12987/97803001598992doi  a(DE-B1597)485666  a(OCoLC)953660917  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aDA209.E6T87 2009 7aBIO0140002bisacsh04a942.03/1092 B1 aTurner, Ralph V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEleanor of Aquitaine :bQueen of France, Queen of England /cRalph V. Turner. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b16 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Maps -- tAcknowledgments -- tGenealogies -- tIntroduction: Searching for a "Truthful Image" of Eleanor of Aquitaine -- t1. Growing Up in the Ducal Court of Aquitaine, 1124-1137 -- t2. Bride to a King, Queen of the French, 1137-1145 -- t3. Adventures and Misadventures on the Second Crusade, 1145-1149 -- t4. A Husband Lost, a Husband Gained, 1149-1154 -- t5. Once More a Queen and Mother: England, 1154-1168 -- t6. A Queen's Work: Regent for an Absentee King, 1155-1168 -- t7. A Taste of Power in Poitou, 1168-1173 -- t8. A Queen's Discontent and her Sons' Thwarted Ambitions, 1173-1174 -- t9. A Captive Queen's Lost Years, 1174-1189 -- t10. The Queen-Mother: Richard's Reign, 1189-1199 -- t11. Securing the Plantagenet Legacy: John's Reign, 1199-1204 -- t12. Overwhelmed by a Black Legend -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEleanor of Aquitaine's extraordinary life seems more likely to be found in the pages of fiction. Proud daughter of a distinguished French dynasty, she married the king of France, Louis VII, then the king of England, Henry II, and gave birth to two sons who rose to take the English throne-Richard the Lionheart and John. Renowned for her beauty, hungry for power, headstrong, and unconventional, Eleanor traveled on crusades, acted as regent for Henry II and later for Richard, incited rebellion, endured a fifteen-year imprisonment, and as an elderly widow still wielded political power with energy and enthusiasm.This gripping biography is the definitive account of the most important queen of the Middle Ages. Ralph Turner, a leading historian of the twelfth century, strips away the myths that have accumulated around Eleanor-the "black legend" of her sexual appetite, for example-and challenges the accounts that relegate her to the shadows of the kings she married and bore. Turner focuses on a wealth of primary sources, including a collection of Eleanor's own documents not previously accessible to scholars, and portrays a woman who sought control of her own destiny in the face of forceful resistance. A queen of unparalleled appeal, Eleanor of Aquitaine retains her power to fascinate even 800 years after her death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aQueenszFrancevBiography. 0aQueenszGreat BritainvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Royalty.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300159899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300159899.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles